 school hostage crisis|Beslan]]\", ''National Nine News'' (Nine Network)\n**\"Iraq Hostage\", ''[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]'' ([[ABC1|ABC TV]])\n**\"Victoria Ganglands\", ''ABC News'' (ABC TV)\n**\"[[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake|Tsunami Disaster]]\", ''[[Ten News]]'' ([[Network Ten]])\n|-\n! width=\"50%\"| Most Outstanding Public Affairs Report\n! width=\"50%\"| Most Outstanding Documentary Series\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''\"[[Backpacker murders|Into the Forest (Ivan Milat) Part 1]]\", ''[[Australian Story]]'' ([[ABC1|ABC TV]])'''\n**\"[[Beslan school hostage crisis|Beslan Prepares for a Funeral]]\", ''[[The 7:30 Report]]'' (ABC TV)\n**\"Coming Clean: Drugs and Cycling\", ''[[60 Minutes (Australian TV program)|60 Minutes]]'' ([[Nine Network]])\n**\"[[Mamdouh Habib|The Trials of Mamdouh Habib]]\", ''[[Dateline (Australian TV program)|Dateline]]'' ([[SBS1|SBS TV]])\n**\"Taliban Country\", ''Dateline'' (SBS TV)\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''The President vs David Hicks'' ([[SBS1|SBS TV]])'''\n**''[[The Last Voices From Heaven|The Last Voices From Heaven Parts 1 & 2]]'' ([[Foxtel]])\n**''Moulin Rouge Girls'' ([[ABC1|ABC TV]])\n**''Stories From a Children's Hospital: Chloe's Story'' (ABC TV)\n**''Tug of Love'' (SBS TV)\n|}\n\n==Performers==\n*[[Mario (American singer)|Mario]]<ref name=\"Logies History\"/>\n*The cast of ''[[Neighbours]]''<ref name=\"Logies History\"/>\n*The cast of ''Grease: The Arena Spectacular''<ref name=\"Logies History\"/>\n*[[Il Divo]]<ref name=\"Logies History\"/>\n*[[Michael Bubl\u00e9]]<ref name=\"Logies History\"/>\n\n==Hall of Fame==\nAfter 20 years on Australian television, ''[[Neighbours]]'' became the 22nd inductee into the TV Week Logies [[List of Logie Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"winners\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb event|0000401/2005}}\n\n{{Logie Awards years}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Logie Awards Of 2005}}\n[[Category:Logie Awards|2005]]\n[[Category:2005 television awards]]\n[[Category:2005 in Australian television]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Update date format tag and add authority control template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logie_Awards_of_2005"}
{"title_page": "Lamborghini 350GTV", "text_new": "{{Infobox automobile\n|name          = Lamborghini 350 GTV{{r|Lambo_350GTV}}\n|image         = Lamborghini 350 GTV.jpg\n|manufacturer  = {{ubl | [[Lamborghini]] (chassis) | Carrozzeria Sargiotto (body) }}\n|production    = 1963\n|assembly      = \n|successor     = [[Lamborghini 350GT|Lamborghini 350 GT]]\n|class         = [[Prototype]] / [[Sports car]]\n|body_style    = 2-[[vehicle door|door]] [[grand tourer]] [[coup\u00e9]]\n|layout        = [[longitudinal engine|Longitudinal]] [[front-engine design|front-engine]], [[rear-wheel drive]]\n|engine        = 3.5&nbsp;[[litre|L]] [[Lamborghini V12|V12]]\n|transmission  = [[list of ZF transmissions#5-speed longitudinal|5-speed ZF]] [[manual transmission|manual]]\n|wheelbase     = {{convert|2450|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|length        = {{convert|4370|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|width         = {{convert|1760|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|height        = {{convert|1050|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|weight        = {{convert|1292|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n|related       = \n|designer      = Giorgio Prevedi, under the supervision of [[Franco Scaglione]]\n|sp            = uk\n}}\n\nThe '''Lamborghini 350 GTV''' was a [[Lamborghini]] [[prototype]] and forerunner of the automaker's first production model, the [[Lamborghini 350GT|350 GT]]. It was first presented to the public at the [[Turin Auto Show#1963|1963 Turin Auto Show]].{{r|Lambo_350GTV}}{{r|RT1994_05p127}}\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Lamborghini 350 GTV rear.jpg|thumb|left|Rear three-quarter view]]\n\nThe design and development of the 350 GTV was overseen by Lamborghini chief engineer [[Gian Paolo Dallara|Gianpaolo Dallara]], assistant [[Paolo Stanzani]] and test driver [[Bob Wallace (test driver)|Bob Wallace]], the core engineering team that developed many early Lamborghini cars. [[Giotto Bizzarrini]] was commissioned to design the engine and an early version of the chassis.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Marchet|first=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/12806744|title=Lamborghini Espada & the 4-seaters : 350GT, 400GT, Islero, Jarama, Marzal, Espada|date=1985|publisher=Osprey Pub.|year=|isbn=0-85045-592-8|location=London|pages=|oclc=12806744}}</ref>\n\nThe 350 GTV's name signified the 3.5 L displacement of the engine, the \"GT\" for [[grand tourer]] and the \"V\" for the Italian word ''\"Veloce''\" (meaning \"fast\").<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nThe 350 GTV body was designed by [[Franco Scaglione]] and built by Carrozzeria Sargiotto in Turin.{{r|Lambo_350GTV}}{{r|RT1994_05p123}} [[Ferruccio Lamborghini]]'s opinion had a significant amount of influence on the design. He reportedly requested styling echoing the [[Aston Martin DB4]]'s tapering rear bodywork and the sleek front of the [[Jaguar E-Type|Jaguar E-type]]. The 350 GTV had many styling details that were unusual at the time of its introduction, including [[Hidden headlamp|hidden headlamps]] and six [[Exhaust system|exhaust tailpipes]] (three on each side of the car's rear). The body was constructed of aluminum and steel. As workers at Sargiotto were primarily skilled in building molds for plastic products, the 350 GTV's body had numerous fit and finish issues.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Lyons|first=Pete|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/18937830|title=The Complete Book of Lamborghini|date=1988|publisher=Beekman House|year=|isbn=0881764892|location=New York|pages=|oclc=18937830}}</ref>\n\nInitially, Bizzarini designed a racing-style [[Space frame#Cars|tubular spaceframe]] chassis for the 350 GTV. [[Neri and Bonacini|Giorgio Neri and Luciano Bonacini]] built the tube frame [[chassis]] in [[Modena]].{{r|LamboCars_350GTV}}<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Borel|first=Jean-Marc|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/9458867|title=Lamborghini|date=[1981?]|publisher=Lamborghini|year=|isbn=2-903652-00-7|location=Bolognese (BO), Italia|pages=|oclc=9458867}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> This design was later reworked by Dallara into a more conventional, heavier design constructed of mostly square and rectangular section tubing that would be used in the production 350 GT.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n[[Ferruccio Lamborghini]] commissioned Giotto Bizzarrini to develop the 350 GTV engine. This was the first iteration of the [[Lamborghini V12]] series of engines, which would power future Lamborghini models up through the end of [[Lamborghini Murci\u00e9lago|Murci\u00e9lago]] production in 2010. Bizzarini developed a 3.5&nbsp;[[litre]] racing-specification [[V12 engine]], with an output of {{convert|255|kW|PS bhp|0|lk=on|abbr=on|sp=}} at 8,000&nbsp;rpm, and [[torque]] of {{convert|326|Nm|0|lk=on|abbr=on}},{{r|Lambo_350GTV}} using the [[Deutsches Institut f\u00fcr Normung|DIN]] measurement standard.{{r|LamboCars_350GTV}}{{r|QV500_350GTV}} This design was derived from Bizzarini's plan for a 1.5 litre [[Formula One]] racing engine.<ref name=\":0\" /> Top speed was claimed by the factory to be {{Convert|280|km/h|mph|abbr=}},<ref name=\":1\" /> although this was an estimate as the car was never driven or tested by the factory.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThis engine had a [[compression ratio]] of 9.5:1 and relatively aggressive [[valve timing]] compared to later versions of the Lamborghini V12. The higher [[redline]], compression ratio and timing made the 350 GTV's engine more suitable for competition use rather than as a comfortable road car. The 350 GTV engine was also equipped with six downdraft [[Weber carburetor|Weber carburetors]] and a [[Dry sump|dry sump lubrication system]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Rive Box|first=Rob de la|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/8431194|title=Lamborghini : the cars from Sant' Agata Bolognese|last2=Crump|first2=Richard|date=1981|publisher=Osprey|others=|year=|isbn=0-85045-408-5|location=London|pages=|oclc=8431194}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe transmission was a 5 speed manual made by [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]]. Power was directed to the rear wheels via a Salisbury [[Locking differential|self-locking differential]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The [[independent suspension]] used triangular wishbones on the front and trapezoidal wishbones on the rear, with telescopic [[Shock absorber|shock absorbers]] and [[Coil spring|coil springs]] at all four corners. Servo-controlled [[Disc brake|disc brakes]] were equipped on all four wheels. The [[Borrani]] [[Centerlock wheel|center locking]] [[Wire wheel|wire wheels]] were fitted with [[Pirelli Cinturato]] HS tires.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Concorso Eleganza Villa d'Este 2013 (8846434749).jpg|alt=350 GTV Interior|thumb|350 GTV Interior]]\nThe 350 GTV was never a complete, driveable car during its time as a Lamborghini prototype.<ref name=\":3\" /> During assembly, the workforce discovered that the body panels would not fit around the engine. Since he had no further plans for the 350 GTV beyond being a show car, Mr. Lamborghini had the engine bay ballasted with bricks and kept the bonnet shut throughout the Turin Auto Show. The incomplete show car also lacked brake calipers, foot pedals and windshield wipers.{{r|RT1994_05p127}}\n\n== Introduction and influence ==\n[[File:1963 Lamborghini 350 GTV Ferruccio e Canestrini.jpg|alt=Ferruccio Lamborghini discussing the newly-introduced 350 GTV with journalist Giovanni Canestrini|left|thumb|Ferruccio Lamborghini (center, with hand outstretched) discussing the newly-introduced 350 GTV with journalist Giovanni Canestrini]]\nThe 350 GTV was introduced to the public at the 1963 Turin Auto Show. It was covered extensively by the press and received both positive and negative reactions.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> A sales brochure was produced and Ferruccio Lamborghini used the unveiling of this prototype to cultivate interest in a production version.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lambocars.com/classic_gt/350_gtv.html|title=350 GTV|last=Smeyers|first=Mark|date=3 January 2016|website=www.lambocars.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> At the time of the 350 GTV's introduction, Mr. Lamborghini told [[Road & Track]] magazine of his intention to make both touring and competition versions of the 350 GTV,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lamm|first=John|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/21/automobiles/a-long-way-from-tractors.html|title=A Long Way From Tractors|date=2013-04-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> although no competition version was ever realized. Lamborghini later garnered a reputation for being reluctant to build racing versions of his cars.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nFerruccio Lamborghini was dissatisfied with several design features of the 350 GTV,{{r|RT1994_05p123}} and with the state of tune of the engine.{{r|LamboCars_350GTV}}{{r|QV500_350GTV}} He commissioned [[Carrozzeria Touring]] to redesign the car to be more practical{{r|RT1994_05p123}} and had the engine detuned to {{convert|270|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 6,500&nbsp;rpm for use in the production car.{{r|LamboCars_350GTV}}{{r|QV500_350GTV}} The compression ratio and redline were lowered and the camshaft profiles altered to moderate the valve timing.<ref name=\":0\" /> The racing-derived dry sump lubrication and downdraft carburetors were also replaced with a simpler [[wet sump]] system and a more common model of Weber sidedraft carburetors.<ref name=\":0\" /> The new body and retuned engine resulted in the first production Lamborghini, the 350 GT.{{r|RT1994_05p127}}\n\n== Later history ==\nAfter the 1963 Turin Auto Show, the 350 GTV was placed into storage at the Lamborghini factory.<ref name=\":0\" /> The 350 GTV remained in storage until the mid-1980s, when car dealer Romano Bernandoni and his cousin, Lamborghini expert Stefano Pasini, convinced the management to sell the 350 GTV to them. Bernandoni and Pasini did not receive the gauges and steering wheel with the car. They did, however, receive several proposals to modify the car into running condition and accepted one. During the modification process, the car's colour was changed from its original pale blue to deep metallic green at the owner's request.{{r|RT1994_05p127}}\n\nThe 350 GTV was then sold to a Japanese collector, who placed the car in the Noritake Collection. Several years later, the 350 GTV was placed on display at the Lamborghini Museum in [[Sant'Agata Bolognese]], Italy.{{r|LamboCars_350GTV}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Lamborghini 350 GTV}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|colwidth=40em|refs=\n<ref name=\"RT1994_05p123\">Lamm, p.123</ref>\n<ref name=\"RT1994_05p127\">Lamm, p.127</ref>\n<ref name=\"Lambo_350GTV\">Automobilpoop Lamborghini Holding SpA: Lamborghini - History - Masterpieces - 350 GTV</ref>\n<ref name=\"LamboCars_350GTV\">LamboCars.com - Lamborghini 350 GTV</ref>\n<ref name=\"QV500_350GTV\">QV500.com - Lamborghini 350 Part 1: 350 GTV</ref>\n}}\n\n;Sources\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Lamm|first=John|editor-first=Thos. L|editor-last=Bryant|date=May 1994|title=Salon: 1963 Lamborghini 350 GTV|journal=Road & Track|volume=45|issue=9|pages=120\u2013127|publisher=Hachette Magazines|location=Newport Beach, California}}\n*{{cite web|title=Automobili Lamborghini Holding SpA: Lamborghini - History - Masterpieces - 350 GTV |url=http://www.lamborghini.com/2006/lamboSitenormal.asp?lang=eng |work=Automobili Lamborghini Holding Spa |publisher=Lamborghini.com |accessdate=10 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107131615/http://www.lamborghini.com/2006/lamboSitenormal.asp?lang=eng |archivedate= 7 January 2010 }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.lambocars.com/archive/older/350gtv.htm|title=Lamborghini 350 GTV|work=[http://www.lambocars.com LamboCars.com]|accessdate=2009-12-26}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.qv500.com/lamborghini350p1.php|title=QV500.com - Lamborghini 350 Part 1: 350 GTV|work=[http://www.qv500.com QV500.com]|accessdate=2009-12-26|archivedate=2008-12-01|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201084315/http://www.qv500.com/lamborghini350p1.php|url-status=dead}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Lamborghini early timeline}}\n{{Lamborghini}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lamborghini 350gtv}}\n[[Category:Lamborghini custom and concept cars|350GTV]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox automobile\n|name          = Lamborghini 350 GTV{{r|Lambo_350GTV}}\n|image         = Lamborghini 350 GTV.jpg\n|manufacturer  = {{ubl | [[Lamborghini]] (chassis) | Carrozzeria Sargiotto (body) }}\n|production    = 1963\n|assembly      = \n|successor     = [[Lamborghini 350GT|Lamborghini 350 GT]]\n|class         = [[Prototype]] / [[Sports car]]\n|body_style    = 2-[[vehicle door|door]] [[grand tourer]] [[coup\u00e9]]\n|layout        = [[longitudinal engine|Longitudinal]] [[front-engine design|front-engine]], [[rear-wheel drive]]\n|engine        = 3.5&nbsp;[[litre|L]] [[Lamborghini V12|V12]]\n|transmission  = [[list of ZF transmissions#5-speed longitudinal|5-speed ZF]] [[manual transmission|manual]]\n|wheelbase     = {{convert|2450|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|length        = {{convert|4370|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|width         = {{convert|1760|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|height        = {{convert|1050|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|weight        = {{convert|1292|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n|related       = \n|designer      = Giorgio Prevedi, under the supervision of [[Franco Scaglione]]\n|sp            = uk\n}}\n\nThe '''Lamborghini 350 GTV''' was a [[Lamborghini]] [[prototype]] and forerunner of the automaker's first production model, the [[Lamborghini 350GT|350 GT]]. It was first presented to the public at the [[Turin Auto Show#1963|1963 Turin Auto Show]].{{r|Lambo_350GTV}}{{r|RT1994_05p127}}\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Lamborghini 350 GTV rear.jpg|thumb|left|Rear three-quarter view]]\n\nThe design and development of the 350 GTV was overseen by Lamborghini chief engineer [[Gian Paolo Dallara|Gianpaolo Dallara]], assistant [[Paolo Stanzani]] and test driver [[Bob Wallace (test driver)|Bob Wallace]], the core engineering team that developed many early Lamborghini cars. [[Giotto Bizzarrini]] was commissioned to design the engine and an early version of the chassis.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Marchet|first=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/12806744|title=Lamborghini Espada & the 4-seaters : 350GT, 400GT, Islero, Jarama, Marzal, Espada|date=1985|publisher=Osprey Pub.|year=|isbn=0-85045-592-8|location=London|pages=|oclc=12806744}}</ref>\n\nThe 350 GTV's name signified the 3.5 L displacement of the engine, the \"GT\" for [[grand tourer]] and the \"V\" for the Italian word ''\"Veloce''\" (meaning \"fast\").<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nThe 350 GTV body was designed by [[Franco Scaglione]] and built by Carrozzeria Sargiotto in Turin.{{r|Lambo_350GTV}}{{r|RT1994_05p123}} Ferruccio Lamborghini's opinion had a significant amount of influence on the design. He reportedly requested styling echoing the [[Aston Martin DB4]]'s tapering rear bodywork and the sleek front of the [[Jaguar E-Type|Jaguar E-type]]. The 350 GTV had many styling details that were unusual at the time of its introduction, including [[Hidden headlamp|hidden headlamps]] and six [[Exhaust system|exhaust tailpipes]] (three on each side of the car's rear). The body was constructed of aluminum and steel. As workers at Sargiotto were primarily skilled in building molds for plastic products, the 350 GTV's body had numerous fit and finish issues.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Lyons|first=Pete|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/18937830|title=The Complete Book of Lamborghini|date=1988|publisher=Beekman House|year=|isbn=0881764892|location=New York|pages=|oclc=18937830}}</ref>\n\nInitially, Bizzarini designed a racing-style [[Space frame#Cars|tubular spaceframe]] chassis for the 350 GTV. [[Neri and Bonacini|Giorgio Neri and Luciano Bonacini]] built the tube frame [[chassis]] in [[Modena]].{{r|LamboCars_350GTV}}<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Borel|first=Jean-Marc|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/9458867|title=Lamborghini|date=[1981?]|publisher=Lamborghini|year=|isbn=2-903652-00-7|location=Bolognese (BO), Italia|pages=|oclc=9458867}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> This design was later reworked by Dallara into a more conventional, heavier design constructed of mostly square and rectangular section tubing that would be used in the production 350 GT.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n[[Ferruccio Lamborghini]] commissioned Giotto Bizzarrini to develop the 350 GTV engine. This was the first iteration of the [[Lamborghini V12]] series of engines, which would power future Lamborghini models up through the end of [[Lamborghini Murci\u00e9lago|Murci\u00e9lago]] production in 2010. Bizzarini developed a 3.5&nbsp;[[litre]] racing-specification [[V12 engine]], with an output of {{convert|255|kW|PS bhp|0|lk=on|abbr=on|sp=}} at 8,000&nbsp;rpm, and [[torque]] of {{convert|326|Nm|0|lk=on|abbr=on}},{{r|Lambo_350GTV}} using the [[Deutsches Institut f\u00fcr Normung|DIN]] measurement standard.{{r|LamboCars_350GTV}}{{r|QV500_350GTV}} This design was derived from Bizzarini's plan for a 1.5 litre [[Formula One]] racing engine.<ref name=\":0\" /> Top speed was claimed by the factory to be {{Convert|280|km/h|mph|abbr=}},<ref name=\":1\" /> although this was an estimate as the car was never driven or tested by the factory.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThis engine had a [[compression ratio]] of 9.5:1 and relatively aggressive [[valve timing]] compared to later versions of the Lamborghini V12. The higher [[redline]], compression ratio and timing made the 350 GTV's engine more suitable for competition use rather than as a comfortable road car. The 350 GTV engine was also equipped with six downdraft [[Weber carburetor|Weber carburetors]] and a [[Dry sump|dry sump lubrication system]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Rive Box|first=Rob de la|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/8431194|title=Lamborghini : the cars from Sant' Agata Bolognese|last2=Crump|first2=Richard|date=1981|publisher=Osprey|others=|year=|isbn=0-85045-408-5|location=London|pages=|oclc=8431194}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe transmission was a 5 speed manual made by [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]]. Power was directed to the rear wheels via a Salisbury [[Locking differential|self-locking differential]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The [[independent suspension]] used triangular wishbones on the front and trapezoidal wishbones on the rear, with telescopic [[Shock absorber|shock absorbers]] and [[Coil spring|coil springs]] at all four corners. Servo-controlled [[Disc brake|disc brakes]] were equipped on all four wheels. The [[Borrani]] [[Centerlock wheel|center locking]] [[Wire wheel|wire wheels]] were fitted with [[Pirelli Cinturato]] HS tires.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Concorso Eleganza Villa d'Este 2013 (8846434749).jpg|alt=350 GTV Interior|thumb|350 GTV Interior]]\nThe 350 GTV was never a complete, driveable car during its time as a Lamborghini prototype.<ref name=\":3\" /> During assembly, the workforce discovered that the body panels would not fit around the engine. Since he had no further plans for the 350 GTV beyond being a show car, Mr. Lamborghini had the engine bay ballasted with bricks and kept the bonnet shut throughout the Turin Auto Show. The incomplete show car also lacked brake calipers, foot pedals and windshield wipers.{{r|RT1994_05p127}}\n\n== Introduction and influence ==\n[[File:1963 Lamborghini 350 GTV Ferruccio e Canestrini.jpg|alt=Ferruccio Lamborghini discussing the newly-introduced 350 GTV with journalist Giovanni Canestrini|left|thumb|Ferruccio Lamborghini (center, with hand outstretched) discussing the newly-introduced 350 GTV with journalist Giovanni Canestrini]]\nThe 350 GTV was introduced to the public at the 1963 Turin Auto Show. It was covered extensively by the press and received both positive and negative reactions.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> A sales brochure was produced and Ferruccio Lamborghini used the unveiling of this prototype to cultivate interest in a production version.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lambocars.com/classic_gt/350_gtv.html|title=350 GTV|last=Smeyers|first=Mark|date=3 January 2016|website=www.lambocars.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> At the time of the 350 GTV's introduction, Mr. Lamborghini told [[Road & Track]] magazine of his intention to make both touring and competition versions of the 350 GTV,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lamm|first=John|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/21/automobiles/a-long-way-from-tractors.html|title=A Long Way From Tractors|date=2013-04-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> although no competition version was ever realized. Lamborghini later garnered a reputation for being reluctant to build racing versions of his cars.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n[[Ferruccio Lamborghini]] was dissatisfied with several design features of the 350 GTV,{{r|RT1994_05p123}} and with the state of tune of the engine.{{r|LamboCars_350GTV}}{{r|QV500_350GTV}} He commissioned [[Carrozzeria Touring]] to redesign the car to be more practical{{r|RT1994_05p123}} and had the engine detuned to {{convert|270|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 6,500&nbsp;rpm for use in the production car.{{r|LamboCars_350GTV}}{{r|QV500_350GTV}} The compression ratio and redline were lowered and the camshaft profiles altered to moderate the valve timing.<ref name=\":0\" /> The racing-derived dry sump lubrication and downdraft carburetors were also replaced with a simpler [[wet sump]] system and a more common model of Weber sidedraft carburetors.<ref name=\":0\" /> The new body and retuned engine resulted in the first production Lamborghini, the 350 GT.{{r|RT1994_05p127}}\n\n== Later history ==\nAfter the 1963 Turin Auto Show, the 350 GTV was placed into storage at the Lamborghini factory.<ref name=\":0\" /> The 350 GTV remained in storage until the mid-1980s, when car dealer Romano Bernandoni and his cousin, Lamborghini expert Stefano Pasini, convinced the management to sell the 350 GTV to them. Bernandoni and Pasini did not receive the gauges and steering wheel with the car. They did, however, receive several proposals to modify the car into running condition and accepted one. During the modification process, the car's colour was changed from its original pale blue to deep metallic green at the owner's request.{{r|RT1994_05p127}}\n\nThe 350 GTV was then sold to a Japanese collector, who placed the car in the Noritake Collection. Several years later, the 350 GTV was placed on display at the Lamborghini Museum in [[Sant'Agata Bolognese]], Italy.{{r|LamboCars_350GTV}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Lamborghini 350 GTV}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|colwidth=40em|refs=\n<ref name=\"RT1994_05p123\">Lamm, p.123</ref>\n<ref name=\"RT1994_05p127\">Lamm, p.127</ref>\n<ref name=\"Lambo_350GTV\">Automobilpoop Lamborghini Holding SpA: Lamborghini - History - Masterpieces - 350 GTV</ref>\n<ref name=\"LamboCars_350GTV\">LamboCars.com - Lamborghini 350 GTV</ref>\n<ref name=\"QV500_350GTV\">QV500.com - Lamborghini 350 Part 1: 350 GTV</ref>\n}}\n\n;Sources\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Lamm|first=John|editor-first=Thos. L|editor-last=Bryant|date=May 1994|title=Salon: 1963 Lamborghini 350 GTV|journal=Road & Track|volume=45|issue=9|pages=120\u2013127|publisher=Hachette Magazines|location=Newport Beach, California}}\n*{{cite web|title=Automobili Lamborghini Holding SpA: Lamborghini - History - Masterpieces - 350 GTV |url=http://www.lamborghini.com/2006/lamboSitenormal.asp?lang=eng |work=Automobili Lamborghini Holding Spa |publisher=Lamborghini.com |accessdate=10 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107131615/http://www.lamborghini.com/2006/lamboSitenormal.asp?lang=eng |archivedate= 7 January 2010 }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.lambocars.com/archive/older/350gtv.htm|title=Lamborghini 350 GTV|work=[http://www.lambocars.com LamboCars.com]|accessdate=2009-12-26}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.qv500.com/lamborghini350p1.php|title=QV500.com - Lamborghini 350 Part 1: 350 GTV|work=[http://www.qv500.com QV500.com]|accessdate=2009-12-26|archivedate=2008-12-01|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201084315/http://www.qv500.com/lamborghini350p1.php|url-status=dead}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Lamborghini early timeline}}\n{{Lamborghini}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lamborghini 350gtv}}\n[[Category:Lamborghini custom and concept cars|350GTV]]\n", "name_user": "Prova MO", "label": "safe", "comment": "move Ferruccio Lamborghini wikilink to first mention of name in article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamborghini_350GTV"}
{"title_page": "Loir-et-Cher's 3rd constituency", "text_new": "{{short description|Constituency of the French Fifth Republic}}\n{{Infobox French constituency\n| name                = 3rd constituency of [[Loir-et-Cher]]\n| image               = MapOfLoir-et-Chers3rdConstituency.png\n| caption             = Loir-et-Cher's 3rd Constituency shown within [[Loir-et-Cher]].\n| map                 = Loir-et-Cher-Position.svg\n| caption2            = Loir-et-Cher within France\n| member-type         = Deputy\n| member              = [[Maurice Leroy]] <ref name=\"assemblee-nationale.fr\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/qui|title=577 D\u00e9put\u00e9s - Assembl\u00e9e nationale|website=www2.assemblee-nationale.fr}}</ref>\n| party-colour        = UDI\n| member-party        = [[Union of Democrats and Independents|UDI]]\n| department          = [[Loir-et-Cher]]\n| region              = \n| canton              =  Drou\u00e9, Herbault, Marchenoir, Mer, Mondoubleau, Montoire-sur-le-Loir, Mor\u00e9e, Ouzouer-le-March\u00e9, Saint-Amand-Longpr\u00e9, Savigny-sur-Braye, Selommes, Vend\u00f4me I, Vend\u00f4me II\n| census-date         = 2017\n| Voters              =  93669 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/elections/carte/2017/resultats|title=Les r\u00e9sultats aux \u00e9lections l\u00e9gislatives de 2017 - Assembl\u00e9e nationale|website=www2.assemblee-nationale.fr}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe 3rd constituency of the [[Loir-et-Cher]] ([[French language|French]]: ''Troisi\u00e8me circonscription de Loir-et-Cher'') is a French legislative [[Constituency (France)|constituency]] in the Seine-Maritime ''[[Departments of France|d\u00e9partement]]''. Like the other 576 French constituencies, it elects one [[National Assembly of France|MP]] using the [[First-past-the-post voting|first past the post]] election system with a run-off.\n\n==Description==\n\nThe 3rd Constituency of the [[Loir-et-Cher]] covers the north west of the department including the medieval town of [[Vend\u00f4me]] on the [[Loir]] river.\n\nThe seat has consistently returned deputies from the centre right. The current incumbent [[Maurice Leroy]] has held the seat for over twenty years.\n\n==Assembly Members==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Election !! Member !! Party\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color: {{Union for French Democracy/meta/color}}\" |  || [[1988 French legislative election|1988]]  || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Jean Desanlis]] || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Union for French Democracy|UDF]]\n|-\n|[[1993 French legislative election|1993]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color: {{Union for French Democracy/meta/color}}\" |  || [[1997 French legislative election|1997]]|| rowspan=\"5\" |[[Maurice Leroy]]|| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Union for French Democracy|UDF]]\n|-\n|[[2002 French legislative election|2002]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color: {{Union of Democrats and Independents/meta/color}}\" |  ||[[2007 French legislative election|2007]]|| rowspan=\"2\" |[[The Centrists|NC]]\n|-\n|[[2012 French legislative election|2012]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Union of Democrats and Independents/meta/color}}\" | || [[2017 French legislative election|2017]] || [[Union of Democrats and Independents|UDI]]\n|}\n\n<ref name=\"assemblee-nationale.fr\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{French National Assembly constituencies}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:French legislative constituencies of Loir-et-Cher|3]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Constituency of the French Fifth Republic}}\n{{Infobox French constituency\n| name                = 3rd constituency of [[Loir-et-Cher]]\n| image               = MapOfLoir-et-Chers3rdConstituency.png\n| caption             = Loir-et-Cher's 3rd Constituency shown within [[Loir-et-Cher]].\n| map                 = Loir-et-Cher-Position.svg\n| caption2            = Loir-et-Cher within France\n| member-type         = Deputy\n| member              = [[Maurice Leroy]] <ref name=\"assemblee-nationale.fr\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/qui|title=577 D\u00e9put\u00e9s - Assembl\u00e9e nationale|website=www2.assemblee-nationale.fr}}</ref>\n| party-colour        = UDI\n| member-party        = [[Union of Democrats and Independents|UDI]]\n| department          = [[Loir-et-Cher]]\n| region              = \n| canton              =  Drou\u00e9, Herbault, Marchenoir, Mer, Mondoubleau, Montoire-sur-le-Loir, Mor\u00e9e, Ouzouer-le-March\u00e9, Saint-Amand-Longpr\u00e9, Savigny-sur-Braye, Selommes, Vend\u00f4me I, Vend\u00f4me II\n| census-date         = 2017\n| Voters              =  93669 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/elections/carte/2017/resultats|title=Les r\u00e9sultats aux \u00e9lections l\u00e9gislatives de 2017 - Assembl\u00e9e nationale|website=www2.assemblee-nationale.fr}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe 3rd constituency of the [[Loir-et-Cher]] ([[French language|French]]: ''Troisi\u00e8me circonscription de Loir-et-Cher'') is a French legislative [[Constituency (France)|constituency]] in the Seine-Maritime ''[[Departments of France|d\u00e9partement]]''. Like the other 576 French constituencies, it elects one [[National Assembly of France|MP]] using the [[First-past-the-post voting|first past the post]] election system with a run-off.\n\n==Description==\n\nThe 3rd Constituency of the [[Loir-et-Cher]] covers the north west of the department including the medieval town of [[Vend\u00f4me]] on the [[Loir]] river.\n\nThe seat has consistently returned deputies from the centre right. The current incumbent [[Maurice Leroy]] has held the seat for over twenty years.\n\n==Assembly Members==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Election !! Member !! Party\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color: {{Union for French Democracy/meta/color}}\" |  || [[1988 French legislative election|1988]]  || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Jean Desanlis]] || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Union for French Democracy|UDF]]\n|-\n|[[1993 